By trying to label Trump supporters as Nazis, Sabato is engaging in a form of ideological gatekeeping. He's leveraging his status as some supposedly well-respected political scientist to decide who belongs within the boundaries of legitimate political discourse and who doesn‚Äôt.

But in doing so, Sabato is actually intensifying the very divide he regularly decries. By declaring Trump‚Äôs supporters as anathema and linking them to the Nazis, he's explicitly casting them as a kind of existential threat. 

And when you treat a political opponent as something to be feared, something beyond the pale, you leave no room for engagement or dialogue.

This is precisely how otherwise normal political divisions deepen into open hostility. One side feels persecuted by another which claims to merely be fighting for "basic human decency" when, in reality, they're pushing for their own explicitly political ends.

As Carl Schmitt once said, "Whoever invokes humanity wants to cheat."

Sabato's unhinged diatribes on Twitter reveal that all attempts to pretend there is a "neutral" objective center ultimately only heighten division because it deludes people into thinking they‚Äôre above the political. 

But no one really is.

When "experts" like Sabato disguise their rampant partisanship as impartial commentary and thoughtful observation, they create an illusion of moral superiority by casting the other side as irrational, dangerous, or even outright evil. 

He claims to fear extreme, divisive rhetoric, all while simultaneously fueling the exact conditions that are making real hostility inevitable.

He deserves what comes next.
